not has* , rather had. Majority of academia has now discarded this notion. This article seriously needs to be updated in line with modern academia as well as the positions of contemporary Muslim academia (such as Azhar, Medina uni, Zaytuna, Nadawatul Ulema, Dar ul Uloom Nadwa, etc)

Made some source corrections. The notion that "all legal issues were solved" or "Mujtahids have ceased to exist" only became normative in the 15th Century, and still was disputed by a minority( Hambalis and majority of Shafiis).

It was the 14th century that phrase "gate of Ijtihad closed" crept into legal terminologies and controversy over it emerged. Also, the notion that "gate of Ijtihad was closed" is now a disproven notion. This was an Orientalist misunderstanding. It has now fell out of favour within the academia as well as Islamic jurists. Every Islamic jurist, Ashari,Maturidi,Salafi, Shi'i, Ibadi have an agreement that this notion is incorrect. It is a discarded notion

Deleted errors pertaining to the source. The source infact stated that the Sunni legal theory on Ijtihad persisted throughout the 14th-19th century despite some claimants that "gates of Ijtihad was closed"
Deleted errors , updated info and made it more im line with source. Schachts outdated 1960s theory reference is not required and is fallen out of the academia
